'<h2>return the anchor part of a URL</h2>\nURL is http://www.example.com/test.htm#part2\nvar x = location.hash;	#part2, return the anchor part of a URL\n$(document).ready(function() {\n    if(window.location.hash.length > 0) {\n        window.scrollTo(0, $(window.location.hash).offset().top);\n    }\n});\nif (window.location.hash.length > 0) {\n setTimeout(function() {\n  window.scrollTo(0, $(window.location.hash).offset().top); }, 100);\n}\ndocument.location.reload() stores the position\nAdd additional true parameter to force reload, but without restoring the position.\ndocument.location.reload(true)\n',
'<h2>Preload, prefetch</h2>\n<a href="https://3perf.com/blog/link-rels/" class="whitebut ">Preload, prefetch and other link tags</a>\nThere’re multiple ways to improve web performance. \nOne of those ways is to preload content you’ll need later in advance. Prefetch a CSS file, prerender a full page, or resolve a domain ahead of time – and you won’t have to wait for it when it’s actually needed!\nThere’re five link rel tags that instruct the browser to preload something:\nlink rel="prefetch"\nlink rel="preload"\nlink rel="preconnect"\nlink rel="dns-prefetch"\nlink rel="prerender"\ndns-prefetch	preemptively perform DNS resolution for the target resource\'s origin\npreconnect	preemptively connect to the target resource\'s origin.\nprefetch	preemptively fetch and cache the target resource as it is likely to be required for a follow-up navigation\npreload	preemptively fetch and cache the target resource for current navigation according to the destination given by the "as" attribute (and the priority associated with that destination).\nprerender	pre-render (load) the specified webpage in the background. \nSo, if the user navigates to this page, it speeds up the page load (because the page is already loaded). \nWarning! This waste the user\'s bandwidth! Only use prerender if it is absolutely sure that the webpage is required at some point in the user journey\n',
